Subnets.

A subnet is a slice of the network's address range confined to a single availability zone. The labels public and private are not properties of the subnet itself; they're a consequence of the route table the subnet is associated with. A subnet is public because its route table has a route to an internet gateway, and private because it doesn't, and the same subnet flips identity the moment you associate it with a different route table.

AWS reserves five addresses in every subnet, the first four and the last, so a slash-twenty-four gives you two hundred fifty-one usable addresses rather than two hundred fifty-six; this bites when you size a small subnet for a function attachment or an endpoint and come up short. Each subnet has an auto-assign-public-address flag, on for default public subnets and off in custom networks.

The canonical pattern is three tiers across two or three zones, public subnets for load balancers and nat, private subnets for application servers, and isolated subnets for databases, so that a zone failure never takes more than one tier offline.
